I"·<h1 id="slicing-a-vector">Slicing a Vector</h1>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Get Slice 
Imagine a situation where you need to get a portion of a vector. Rust allows you to borrow the slice of the vector instead of using the whole vector.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Syntax 
Slice is a two-word object. The first word is a pointer to the data, and the second word is the length of the slice.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>fn main() {
   // define a vector of size 5
   let my_vec = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
   let slice:&amp;[i32] = &amp;my_vec[2..4];
   // print the vector
   println!("Slice of the vector : {:?}",slice);
}

</code></pre></div></div>
<p>output</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Slice of the vector : [3, 4]

</code></pre></div></div>

